	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Fish exports help combat hunger, but better management is needed</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 May 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The 10th meeting of the FAO sub-committee on fish trade, held in Spain from May 30th to June 2nd 2006, was marked by vigorous debate on the increasingly complex challenges in managing the globe-spanning fish-trade sector responsibly.</p><p> Questions regarding new standards for safety, quality, traceability and eco-labelling, that are increasingly being imposed on fish imports by many authorities and retailers in the developed world, featured prominently in the discussions. Developing countries in particular noted that complying with such standards involves significant financial and technical burdens, especially since they are not universal but often vary greatly from market to market. The Chair of the meeting commented that different standards applied to fish imports can create confusion and difficulties, especially for countries where production comes from small-scale fishers.</p><p> An FAO report presented at the meeting said that there was no proof so far that fish trade had a detrimental effect on the amount of fish available for consumption as food in poor countries. However, more rigorous resource management is critical in order to ensure the sustainability of fisheries and the future of the fish-export sector. ‘The fish trade helps poor countries shore up their food-security situation’ said the director of the FAO's fisheries industry division, ‘but increasing international demand can at times result in excessive fishing pressure, leading to the over-fishing and wasteful use of stocks ... Meeting demand must be balanced with sustainable management if developing countries want to continue to benefit in this way.’</p><p>
 Though participating countries endorsed the idea of a voluntary set of guidelines aimed at ensuring that the fish trade does not undermine the responsible management of fisheries resources, they stopped short of adopting them. Instead, they recommended that the guidelines undergo additional work in order to better reflect ongoing changes in the international regimes governing fish trade.<br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> FAO newsroom, June 6th 2006</p><p>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2006/1000314/index.html" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2006/1000314/index.html</a> <br/> FAO press release, May 30th 2006</p><p>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2006/1000301/index.html" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2006/1000301/index.html</a> <br/> ‘Responsible fish trade and food security’, FAO fisheries technical paper 456, 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=2168" target="_self">http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=2168</a> <br/> Meeting documents available from</p><p>

<a href="ftp://ftp.fao.org/FI/DOCUMENT/COFI/cofift_10/Default.htm" target="_self">ftp://ftp.fao.org/FI/DOCUMENT/COFI/cofift_10/Default.htm</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> There is increasing recognition that if fish trade is to continue bringing benefits, it has to be based on the sustainable exploitation of resources. This implicitly acknowledges that the current model of exploitation and use of fish resources is not sustainable. Changing the model requires not only assigning the appropriate means to fisheries management, in all its components (control, research, participation of stakeholders, etc), but also regulating market forces in ways that do not encourage over-exploitation.</p><p> The FAO voluntary guidelines on responsible fish trade could be a useful tool. However, the dynamic nature of the fish trade, along with its diversity, do not make the exercise easy. Moreover, ways must be found to ensure that such guidelines inform the discussions and negotiations taking place in other forums, such as the WTO.</p>
		</div>
		
